post_text:
Last night, the STRIDE School Board approved a Distance Learning Plan for the first trimester of the year. All students will participate in distance learning full-time.

Please join us in making distance learning better, more equitable, and more effective. We have put a lot of time and energy into our distance learning plan. We knew that no matter what plan STRIDE put in place, not all families would agree. We understand and are here to help and support you. Let us know how we can help - we are here for you. Our families, students, and staff members are what makes STRIDE successful, and we WILL continue that success throughout distance learning. We miss our students and our families. We can't WAIT to see you when school opens.

Check out our website for our distance learning plan.
https://strideacademy.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/Distance-Learning-2020-2021-8.7.2020-1.pdf

Minnesota Department of Education
June 24 at 3:35 PM ·

Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) can provide families with children up to $325 for groceries. The Minnesota Department of Human Services says as many as 150,000 families may be eligible for these additional food assistance benefits. The application is available in Hmong, Russian, Somali, Spanish and Vietnamese. Apply by June 30. https://mn.p-ebt.org/

For help in applying call 651-431-4050 or 800-657-3698, Monday - Friday from 8 a.m. - 4 p.m.

Minnesota is now offering funds for families of children ages 5 to 18 who qualify for free or reduced-price school
meals. The new program, called Pandemic EBT (P-EBT), will provide up to $325 per child that families can use to
purchase nutritious food for their household. Approximately 350,000 Minnesota children could benefit.

Learn more at: www.mn.p-ebt.org

post_text:
Though tomorrow won’t be the same as the last day of school in the past, we are very much looking forward to seeing all of our families in a drive-thru style goodbye tomorrow, 9:30-2:00.

While many things have changed over the last 2.5 months, there are still many things that haven’t. We still get to see our student’s smiling faces, now over Zoom, Seesaw, and Google. We still get to hear about the fun things you have done at home. And, most importantly, our students are STILL the reason their teacher’s days are filled with laughs and smiles.

We have missed our students. We have missed our families. Though distance learning has not been ideal for most (if not all), we want our students, teachers, and especially parents, to know that we are proud of you. We know you worked hard. We know it wasn’t easy. We know there were days it was a struggle. You did your best and we couldn’t be prouder of you.

Parents - we thank you and appreciate you. 🙌🏼

We look forward to￼ seeing our families tomorrow - drive-thru, social distance style!

post_text:
Today was a tough day for our staff and families. We will continue our distance learning for the remainder of the school year. Though it is not what any of us want, we know Governor Tim Walz did not have an easy time making this decision. He is doing what is best for Minnesota students and families, and for that we are grateful.

We want you to know that we will continue to be here for our families, we will continue our distance learning, and we will continue to support you through it all. We know this isn’t easy or ideal, and we are so proud of our students and staff. We are all in this together. Hang in there!

With schools closed nationwide, supporting students in the most need with basic learning tools is critical. Not only are pencils the #1-requested item from teachers year after year, but they support both cognitive and motor skills for children. Thanks to @mybicpen’s generosity and support, for each post that includes #PostForPencils, 20 pencils will be provided to underserved students through @kidsinneed. For more info visit: www.kinf.org/postforpencils.

post_text:
A couple of items:
1. There is NO SCHOOL tomorrow, April 10, and Monday, April 13. You do NOT need to check in with teachers these days. This also means that there is no school lunch pick-up, and no bus stop lunch deliveries those two days.
2. The second packet pick-up for distance learning will be on Tuesday, April 14. Drive through the pick-up line between 8-2 and we will bring your work out to you - just like last time! Do not return your old packets when coming through.
3. It is very important that you do your work and check in with your teacher everyday so you are not marked absent.
4. We hope all of our families are staying safe and well. We miss you!
text:
A couple of items:
1. There is NO SCHOOL tomorrow, April 10, and Monday, April 13. You do NOT need to check in with teachers these days. This also means that there is no school lunch pick-up, and no bus stop lunch deliveries those two days.
2. The second packet pick-up for distance learning will be on Tuesday, April 14. Drive through the pick-up line between 8-2 and we will bring your work out to you - just like last time! Do not return your old packets when coming through.
3. It is very important that you do your work and check in with your teacher everyday so you are not marked absent.
4. We hope all of our families are staying safe and well. We miss you!

post_text: As we head into our second week of distance learning, we’d like to take this opportunity to thank our parents and students. This has been quite the adjustment for all of you, and we appreciate the time, effort, and work you are putting in. We know many families are trying to balance it all, and we just want to let you know that we see that and you are doing great. We miss all of our students and we are here for you. Keep up the great work!

post_text:
Tomorrow we start distance learning! Thank you to our families for your patience and understanding as we have prepared for this. There are a few things you should know:

1. WE MISS OUR STUDENTS. A LOT. 💚
2. Materials can be picked up tomorrow. Pull up in the pick up lane and we will bring everything out to you. Please do not get out of your car.
3. We are here to help you through this and support you. Please do not hesitate to contact your child’s teacher if you need anything!
4. The school will remain closed during this time, with the exception of driving through the pick up lane to have lunch brought out to you. We will also continue to drop lunches off by bus throughout this time.
5. Your child’s emotional well-being is important during this time. Here is a resource to help you navigate through.
https://www.childtrends.org/publications/resources-for-supporting-childrens-emotional-well-being-during-the-covid-19-pandemic

post_text:
Congratulations to Diane Moeller on receiving the 2019 St. Cloud State University Distinguished Alumni Award. Diane has influenced many lives throughout her career as a teacher and an administrator. STRIDE Academy is so fortunate to have benefited from Diane’s leadership. For the last 2 1/2 years, Diane has championed the turnaround of our school. Thanks to her leadership, STRIDE Academy is not only surviving. . . it is thriving once again!

Congratulations, Mrs. Moeller!
shared_text:
St. Cloud State University Alumni Association
September 30, 2019 at 12:30 PM ·

The 2018-19 Distinguished Alumni Award recipient is Diane Moeller ’77 ’82, who graduated summa cum laude from St. Cloud State University in 1977 with a Bachelor of Science Degree in Elementary Education with a minor in Music. In 1982, she earned a Master of Education degree from St. Cloud State.

Congratulations, Diane!

post_text:
Mayor Kleis stopped by on Tuesday to give our 5th & 6th grade students a pep talk before they head to Junior Achievement in the St. Cloud Area Biztown next week! Students have had several weeks of classroom training that they will put to use when they go to Biztown, which is a 12,000 square foot simulated city in St. Paul.

Students will learn what it takes to run a successful business, manage bank accounts, and make important business and personal finance decisions in their assigned Biztown shop. Students will apply what they’ve learned in class to their Biztown shop, and learn how it can be applied to the “real world.”

post_text: On Tuesday, STRIDE teachers participated in an in-service on Culturally Responsive Teaching. We are so proud of our staff's commitment to meeting this challenge! #toppriortiy.
